Statements:
[
    "REST APIs are an important concept in modern web development.",
    "REST stands for Representational State Transfer.",
    "REST is not a protocol like HTTP.",
    "REST is a style of building web APIs.",
    "REST is a set of architectural guidelines for designing and building APIs.",
    "REST APIs expose data and operations (actions) that can be performed.",
    "REST APIs provide a way to interact with data, not just send raw data.",
    "REST APIs do not necessarily transfer complete state between client and server.",
    "REST APIs focus on request-response interactions.",
    "The client sends a request, the server processes it, and sends a response back.",
    "REST is more about what happens than how it happens.",
    "REST principles encourage building APIs that are adaptable.",
    "REST principles encourage building APIs that can handle more traffic and new functionalities.",
    "REST APIs are built around resources.",
    "Resources are things you want to manage, such as a user, product, or blog post.",
    "Each resource typically has a unique identifier.",
    "A unique identifier could be something like /users/123.",
    "Each resource has metadata, such as a user's name or email address.",
    "REST APIs use HTTP methods (verbs) to represent actions.",
    "GET is used to retrieve a resource.",
    "POST is used to create a new resource.",
    "PUT is used to update an existing resource.",
    "PATCH is used to modify an existing resource.",
    "DELETE is used to delete a resource.",
    "Each request from the client to the server contains all the information needed to process that request.",
    "The server does not store any client context between requests.",
    "REST APIs are stateless.",
    "Statelessness makes the system scalable.",
    "REST APIs use a uniform interface.",
    "A uniform interface means a consistent way for clients and servers to communicate.",
    "Standard HTTP methods and data formats are used in REST APIs.",
    "JSON is the most popular data format for REST APIs.",
    "JSON is lightweight and easy to read.",
    "XML is another data format, less common now but still used in some legacy systems.",
    "REST APIs are simple and straightforward to understand.",
    "The stateless nature of REST APIs makes them easier to scale.",
    "REST APIs are flexible.",
    "Different clients can interact with the same API in different ways.",
    "Almost all web browsers and servers support HTTP.",
    "REST is a standard, making it easier for developers to work together.",
    "A REST API for a blog could allow clients to GET /posts to get a list of all blog posts.",
    "A REST API for a blog could allow clients to POST /posts to create a new blog post.",
    "A REST API for a blog could allow clients to GET /posts/{id} to get details of a specific blog post.",
    "A REST API for a blog could allow clients to PUT /posts/{id} to update an existing blog post.",
    "A REST API for a blog could allow clients to DELETE /posts/{id} to delete a blog post.",
    "REST APIs are a foundational way for building web services.",
    "REST APIs are designed to be scalable, flexible, and easy to integrate.",
    "There are resources available for further learning about REST APIs.",
    "REST API Explained is a resource for learning about REST APIs.",
    "RESTful API Design by Google Developers is a resource for learning about REST APIs.",
    "Understanding REST Architecture by W3Schools is a resource for learning about REST APIs.",
    "The user is asked if they want to delve deeper into specific aspects of REST APIs.",
    "Specific aspects offered include HTTP methods, JSON data formats, and API design principles."
